The stack trace points to `LoopVectorizationPlanner::buildVPlansWithVPRecipes` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`. This function seems to be where the vectorization plan is constructed. Inside this function, it calls the `VFRange` constructor. I'll search for where `VFRange` is constructed within this function.

Looking at the source code for `LoopVectorizationPlanner::buildVPlansWithVPRecipes`, I see this line:
`VFRange VFs(MinVF, MaxVF);`
The assertion fails in this constructor, meaning `MaxVF` is not a power of two. `MaxVF` is calculated earlier in the function.

The relevant logic seems to be where `MaxVF` is constrained by memory checks. For scalable vectors, the code calculates a `MaxSafeElements` based on dependence distances.

```cpp
// In LoopVectorizationPlanner::buildVPlansWithVPRecipes
...
if (IsScalable) {
  // Clamp the max VF to the max safe VF.
  if (auto MaxSafeElements = Legal->getMaxSafeScalableVF())
    MaxVF = std::min(MaxVF, ElementCount::getScalable(*MaxSafeElements));
}
...
VFRange VFs(MinVF, MaxVF); // Crash here
```

The function `Legal->getMaxSafeScalableVF()` in `LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp` is the place to investigate. It calculates the maximum safe scalable vectorization factor based on memory dependencies.

```cpp
// In LoopVectorizationLegality::getMaxSafeScalableVF
...
for (const auto &Dep : Dependences) {
  ...
  if (Dep.isScalar()) {
    ...
    if (auto Distance = Dep.getDistance()) {
      uint64_t MaxSafeVF = Distance->Value / InstBytes;
      MaxVF = std::min(MaxVF, MaxSafeVF);
    }
...
```

Here, `MaxSafeVF` is calculated as `Distance / InstBytes`. In our case, `Distance` is 192 and `InstBytes` (size of `i16`) is 2, so `MaxSafeVF` is 96. This value is not a power of two. The result of `getMaxSafeScalableVF` is then used as the `End` for `VFRange`, which asserts that `End` must be a power of two.

### The Fix

The fix is to ensure that the calculated maximum safe VF is rounded down to the nearest power of two before it is returned from `getMaxSafeScalableVF`. The `llvm::PowerOf2Floor` function can be used for this.

I will modify `LoopVectorizationLegality::getMaxSafeScalableVF` to apply `PowerOf2Floor` to the calculated `MaxSafeVF`.

```cpp
// In LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp
...
      uint64_t MaxSafeVF = Distance->Value / InstBytes;
      // The VFs we're going to probe are all powers of 2, so we can
      // round down to the nearest power of 2.
      if (MaxSafeVF == 0)
        return 0;
      MaxVF = std::min(MaxVF, PowerOf2Floor(MaxSafeVF));
...
```
This change ensures that the value used to construct `VFRange` is always a power of two (or zero), satisfying the assertion.

I will now apply this change using `sed`.

```bash
sed -i 's/MaxVF = std::min(MaxVF, MaxSafeVF);/if (MaxSafeVF == 0) return 0; MaxVF = std::min(MaxVF, PowerOf2Floor(MaxSafeVF));/' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp
```

